Getting help, and the shape of the docker command line.

You will not memorise every flag of every command, and you don't need to. The command line has a regular shape, and its built-in help is excellent, so you can always find your way.

Start with the shape. Every command is docker, then an object, then a verb, then any flags and arguments. Once you know the objects, you can guess the commands. The objects include container, image, volume, and network, plus system, builder, compose, context, secret, service, stack, and swarm. And the verb names repeat across objects: list, inspect, remove, prune. So docker volume list and docker network list behave exactly the way you'd expect.

The built-in help goes three levels deep. Docker, with the help flag, gives you the top-level list of objects and commands. An object followed by the help flag, like docker container help, lists every verb for that object. And an object and verb followed by the help flag, like docker run help, lists every flag of that one command. Docker run help is the single most-read help page in all of Docker. For deeper reference, there's docs dot docker dot com, which is current and searchable, and every official image on Docker Hub ships a read-me covering its tags, environment variables, and volumes.

Finally, cleaning up. A few hours into Docker, you'll have dozens of exited containers and old images lying around. You can remove them one at a time, or in bulk with docker system prune, which clears stopped containers, dangling images, and unused networks. Add dash a to also remove all unused images, and add the volumes flag to also wipe unused volumes, but be careful, because that last one is real data loss. The habit that saves you is simple: when you're stuck, run the command with the help flag first, and reach for the docs second. That closes module one. You can now run, list, inspect, and clean up containers, and you understand the map, from client, to daemon, to image, to container, to registry, that the rest of the course fills in.
